==In culture==
{{in popular culture|date=January 2011}}
* [[William Blake]] famously [[William Blake's Illustrations of the Book of Job|illustrated]] the Book of Job, including imagery of Satan.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/30526 Illustrations of The Book of Job by William Blake]&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Ralph Vaughan Williams]]' orchestral work, ''[[Job: A Masque for Dancing]]'' was directly inspired by Blake's work.
* [[Joni Mitchell]]'s song The Sire of Sorrow (Job's Sad Song), on ''[[Turbulent Indigo]]'', is inspired by the Book of Job.
* Sir [[Peter Maxwell Davies]] composed an [[oratorio]], ''Job'', to the text of the [[Stephen Mitchell (translator)|Stephen Mitchell]] translation, focusing on the moral questions it raises.
* [[Brett Gurewitz]], &quot;[[Sorrow (Bad Religion song)]]&quot;
* [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], ''[[Prayer (song)]]''
* The Golden Gate Quartet have a song about Job [http://www.rhapsody.com/goldengatejubileequartet]
* [[O Brother Where Art Thou]] - [[Constant Sorrow]]
* The two part play [[Goethe's Faust|''Faust'']] by [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]] is inspired by the Book of Job
* [[U2]]'s song &quot;[[Ultraviolet (Light My Way)]]&quot; is an interpretation of the story of Job
* [[Smashing Pumpkins]]' song &quot;[[Bullet With Butterfly Wings]]&quot; mentions Job
* [[Godspell]]' song All For the Best &quot;...Your mood and your robe Are both a deep blue, You'd bet that Job Had nothing on you...&quot;
* In the film [[Mission: Impossible (film)|''Mission: Impossible'']] the antagonists codename their operation Job 314, a reference to the chapter 3, verse 14 of the book of Job.
* [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]] is told the story of Job by his parents in the episode [[Cartmanland]] of [[South Park]] (and is disgusted by his perception of the immorality of God playing sick games with a perfectly [[innocent]] man simply to prove a point to Satan).
* [[The Coen Brothers]] have a 2009 film called &quot;[[A Serious Man]]&quot; which is a modern telling of the book of Job.
* [[Book of Job in Byzantine illuminated manuscripts|Book of Job in Byzantine Illuminated Manuscripts]]
* [[Jan Garbarek]]'s song &quot;[[Parce Mihi Domine]]&quot; is an interpretation of the verses from the Book of Job
* In the 1991 Movie [[Cape Fear (1991 film)|Cape Fear]] Max Cady advises Sam Bowden to check out &quot;the book between Esther and Psalms&quot;. This is later revealed to be the book of Job, which Bowden reads later in the movie.
* The forthcoming biography of [[Apple]] founder and CEO [[Steve Jobs]] entitled &quot;iSteve: The Book of Jobs&quot; is both a reference to - and directly inspired by - the Book of Job.

